HW16: PCA Ordination for Stickleback RNA-Seq

Introduction

The problem: Small et al.2016 conducted an experiment to determine factors that influence gene expression in the gut of stickleback. The main question is the influence of the gut microbiome on gene expression. It is also possible that other factors could influencd transcription, such as the source population of the fish, the genotype (family), or the flask the fish were raised in.

Experimental design and data file information: The dataframe is comprised of 89 columns and 15,847 rows. Each row is a gene. The first 5 columns give information about the gene: Ensembl gene name, scaffold location of gene in genome, bp location of gene start position, gene description from ZFIN, and gene symbol. The columns 6-89 are the normalized expression levels for each fish. Gene expression is normalized so reported in terms of FPKM (Fragments Per Kilobase of transcript per Million mapped reads). These columns are named with the individual fish/genomic library ID, and additional information associated with each ID is provided in the metadata file. The metadata file provides information on the population (FW/OC), family (FW 1-3/ OC 1-2), treatment (CV/ GF), sex (M/F), and flask (1A-D, 3A-C, 4B-F, 5A-D, 6A-C).

Plan: To understand gut transcriptome patterns of variation, I will perform PCA ordination. I will plot each individual fish (which is one RNA-seq library) onto the major axes of variation to collapse multidimensional variation to two dimenstions. I will map experimental treatment, population, and family on the plot to determine whether any of these factors help explain overall transcriptional variation. I will also determine the genes that contribute most to the variation across samples.

PCA ordination

I used the R function prcomp to calculate the similarity matrix and determine the major axes of variatin. The bar graph below shows the percent variation explained by each of the principal components. There cannot be more than 84 PCs because this is the number of samples we have. The first 16 PCs explain more than 1% of the variance (dotted line is across 1%); the rest of the PCs seem negligible. There is not a clear drop-off point, but I decided to show the first 3 PCs in my plots. The first 3 PCs explain 35.2% of the variation, which is a substantial amount.

Experimental treatment status mapped to PCA plot suggests conventional and germ-free treatments do not explain transcriptional variation

Below is the PCA plot, with each dot representing one fish and its place in transcription space on PC1 vs PC2 and PC2 vs PC3. The experimental treatments are mapped in different colors and sex is depicted with M/F above each dot. Neither treatment nor sex seem to contribute to transcriptional variation on these PCs that explain 35.2% of the variation. This plot suggests the microbiome does not contribute greatly to transcriptional variation in these fish.

Population (Ocean/Freshwater) explains transcriptional variation

In contrast to the microbiome, the source population of the fish (ocean or freshwater) does group together, suggesting population contributes notably t transcriptional variation. This separation by population is noticable when plotting PC1 vs.PC2, but it is even more noticable when plotting PC2 vs.PC3. This suggests PC2 and PC3 mainly explain variation due to populatoin, and PC1 accounts for some other source of unknown variation.

Family effect (genotype effect) does not explain variation

Since the different populations represent fish from different genotypes, I wanted to check another genotype effect, that of family. I next checked whether the family of fish seems to contribute to variation. I mapped all 5 families onto the PCA plot. We see again the effect of population (OC vs FW), but it is hard to tell an effect of family.

To more closely investigate family, I re-ran the PCA with prcomp separately for each population. The two PCA plots are shown below. The families do not seem well-separated, suggesting the genotype effect is prevalent only for more extreme genotype differences (population) and not for smaller genotypic differences due to family.

Genes that contribute to population differences on PC3

It seems that PC3 explains variation due at least partly to population. I found the genes that contribute to PC3 by obtaining the loadings of the PCA for PC3. A value is calculated for each gene indicating how much the gene contributes to variation in the given PC. Each gene contributes a very small amount to the PC, and there is not a sharp difference between a top number of genes and the rest. This would indicate that just a few genes explain most of the variation, and perhaps these genes would explain differences between freshwater and ocean stickleback. Shown below are the top 10,000 genes. Their loading values decrease steadily.

Nevertheless, perhaps the genes with the top loadings can still tell us something about factors that differentiate marine and freshwater stickleback. Future directions of this work will include determining whether these genes are enriched in GO terms. I could also do this GO analysis for the genes from the other loadings. I would also like to know whether the genes that contribute to the population PC have been previously implicated in differentiating marine and freshwater stickleback.
